he research project\n\nFigure 2: FAIR-DSM maturity levels. Figure taken from https://fairplus.github.io/Data- Maturity/\n\nR4ALL - SOP \u2013 FAIR data assessment\n\nPage: 3/9\n\n4 9 01 06.01.25\n\n4.2\n\nAssessment of FAIRness level of dataset\n\nThe process of evaluation of FAIR level of a dataset involves the several key steps:\n\n1. Nomination of a dataset\n\nDANnkwWN\n\n2. Identification of stakeholders\n\n3. Pre-FAIRification assessment\n\n4. Task force establishment\n\n5. Agile-based tasks sprints\n\n6. Post-FAIRification assessment\n\nNomination of a dataset\n\nThe first step in evaluating a dataset's FAIRness level is to identify and nominate a dataset. In this context, a dataset is a collection of files that represent information in a predefined format and capture data within a similar context. This selected dataset then becomes the basis for the FAIR assessment and subsequent improvement steps. Examples of datasets include an Excel sheet containing experimental endpoint results, such as IC50 values for a compound library, or an analysis report in PDF or Word format from an instrument-based analysis.", "metadata": {"doc_id": "7c1615a6-e8dc-4bce-b23f-8b7e20185a95", "content_type": "CompositeElement", "filename": "R4ALL_SOP_FairDataAssessment.pdf"}}